'''Corey Ian Haim''' (December 23, 1971 <U+2013> March 10, 2010)<ref>[http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/03/10/AR2010031001225.html 'Lost Boys' actor Corey Haim dead in Burbank at 38]</ref><ref>[http://newsolio.com/rip-corey-haim-80s-teen-heartthrob-in-suspected-drug-overdose,6607 RIP Corey Haim, 80's Teen Heartthrob in Suspected Drug Overdose]</ref> was a [[Canada|Canadian]] actor, known for a 1980s [[Hollywood]] career as a teen idol. He starred or co-starred in a number of films such as ''[[Lucas (film)|Lucas]]'', ''[[Murphy's Romance]]'', ''[[The Lost Boys]]'', ''[[License to Drive]]'' and ''[[Dream a Little Dream]]''. Most notably, he collaborated numerous times with [[Corey Feldman]], the pair being dubbed "[[The Two Coreys]]". Haim and Feldman starred in a TV 'reality' show titled ''[[The Two Coreys (TV series)|The Two Coreys]]'',<ref>[http://www.aetv.com/the-two-coreys/ A&E's ''The Two Coreys'' website]</ref> which aired on the [[A&E Network]] from 2007 to 2008.

==Early life==
Haim was born in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada, the son of Judy, an [[Israel]]i-born data processor, and Bernie Haim, who worked in sales.<ref name="ref1985">{{cite news|last=Zekas|first=Rick|coauthors=|title=North York kid sees his future in Hollywood|pages=|publisher=The Toronto Star|date=1985-10-15|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/thestar/access/474652321.html?dids=474652321:474652321&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Oct+15%2C+1985&author=Rita+Zekas+Toronto+Star&pub=Toronto+Star&desc=North+York+kid+sees+his+future+in+Hollywood&pqatl=google|accessdate=2010-03-10}}</ref> He had an older sister, Carol.<ref name="ref1984"/> Haim was raised [[Jew]]ish.<ref name="ref1984">{{cite news|last=Schnurmacher|first=Thomas|coauthors=|title=Funny boy gets a film break|pages=36|publisher=The Montreal Gazette|date=1984-11-10|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=EkUwAAAAIBAJ&sjid=paUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4662,5435214&dq=funny-boy-gets-a-film-break&hl=en|accessdate=2010-03-10}}: "His parents Bernie and Judy Haim are preparing for a February bar mitzvah."</ref><ref>[http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20040769_20040772_20046208_2,00.html The Two Coreys: Together again! | Corey Feldman | 2 | THE Q&A | TV | Summer TV | Entertainment Weekly<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He was enrolled in acting lessons by his mother in an attempt to help him overcome his shyness.<ref>[http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0000433/bio Corey Haim trivia] ''[[IMDb]]''</ref> Haim, not particularly fascinated by acting, participated in other activities, such as [[ice hockey]], playing music on his [[Keyboard instrument|keyboard]] and collecting [[comic book]]s.<ref>[http://www.coreyhaim.us/bio.html Corey Haim: Biography<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

==1980s==
Haim first broke into mainstream acting playing the role of Larry in the Canadian family-oriented comedy television series, ''[[The Edison Twins]]'', which ran from 1982 through until 1986. Haim made his first cinematic appearance in the [[1984 in film|1984]] [[feature film]], ''[[Firstborn (film)|Firstborn]]'', which starred [[Sarah Jessica Parker]] and [[Robert Downey Jr]]. In 1985, Haim appeared in minor roles in ''[[Secret Admirer]]'' and ''[[Murphy's Romance]]'' and starred in the leading role in a feature film version of [[Stephen King]]'s [[novella]] ''[[Silver Bullet (film)|Silver Bullet]]'', playing a [[paraplegic]] boy alongside [[Gary Busey]]. Haim started to make a name for himself in the industry, notably by earning his first [[Young Artist Award]] as an Exceptional Young Actor Starring in a Television Special or Movie of the Week for the television movie ''A Time to Live''.

Haim's major break was in 1986, billed as the main star alongside [[Kerri Green]], [[Charlie Sheen]], and [[Winona Ryder]] in the popular movie ''[[Lucas (film)|Lucas]]''. Haim would receive a nomination for an Exceptional Performance by a Young Actor Starring in a Feature Film <U+2013> Comedy or Drama at the Young Artist Awards for his role as the title character. Film critic [[Roger Ebert]] gave Haim good reviews.<ref>Ebert, Roger. [http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19860328/REVIEWS/603280301/1023 Roger Ebert review of ''Lucas'']. ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. March 28, 1986. Retrieved July 30, 2007.</ref> Following the success of ''Lucas'', Haim starred in the 1987 television series ''Roomies''.

In 1987, Haim had a featured role in [[Joel Schumacher]]'s vampire film ''[[The Lost Boys]]'', alongside [[Jason Patric]] and [[Kiefer Sutherland]]. The film was well received by most reviewers.<ref>[http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/lost_boys/ The Lost Boys Movie Reviews, Pictures <U+2013> Rotten Tomatoes<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Besides gaining Haim more renown, the film began his famous partnership with Feldman. The performance earned him another Young Artist Award nomination as Best Young Male Superstar in a Motion Picture. In 1988, Haim starred in two more widely released films: ''[[License to Drive]]'', a financially successful teen comedy co-starring Feldman, and the horror film ''[[Watchers (1988 film)|Watchers]]''. Haim won his second Young Artist Award, tying Feldman for the Best Young Actor in a Motion Picture Comedy or Fantasy award for ''License to Drive''.

Haim and Feldman appeared in the film ''[[Dream a Little Dream]]''. The film spawned the [[Billboard Hot 100]] number one single ''[[Rock On (Michael Damian song)|Rock On]]'' for [[Michael Damian]], with the pair appearing in the song's music video. That year Haim released a self-promotional [[video]] [[documentary film|documentary]] entitled ''Corey Haim: Me, Myself, and I''.

==1990s==
Haim's first film after the ''Me, Myself and I'' documentary was ''[[The Dream Machine]],'' a [[direct-to-video]] film released in 1990. Haim co-starred with [[Patricia Arquette]] in ''[[Prayer of the Rollerboys]]''. He continued starring in direct-to-video films, including ''[[Blown Away (1992 film)|Blown Away]]'',<ref>[http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0103843/ Blown Away (1992)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> ''[[The Double 0 Kid]]'' and ''[[Oh, What a Night (film)|Oh, What a Night]]''. In 1993, he starred in a full motion [[video game]] called ''[[Double Switch (video game)|Double Switch]]'', which was released for the [[Sega CD]] and later for the [[Sega Saturn]], as well as for the home computer. Over the next two years, Haim would release sequels to two of his older films; in 1994, ''[[Fast Getaway II]]'' was released along with ''[[National Lampoon's Last Resort]]''. The following year, ''[[Life 101]]'' and another sequel, ''[[Dream a Little Dream 2]]'', with Feldman, were released.

In 1996, Haim starred in four more direct-to-video films: ''[[Snowboard Academy]]'', ''[[Busted (film)|Busted]]'' with Feldman, ''[[Demolition High]]'', and ''[[Fever Lake]]''. He had a minor role in a television version of ''[[Merlin (film)|Merlin]]''. After releasing both ''[[Never Too Late (film)|Never Too Late]]'' and the sequel to ''Demolition High'', ''[[Demolition University]]'' (which he produced), he filed for [[bankruptcy]] in 1997.

==2000s==
Haim attempted to return to the industry in 2000 with another direct-to-video film, ''Without Malice'', with [[Jennifer Beals]] and [[Craig Sheffer]]. He spent time in rehab. Haim says, "I started on the downers which were a hell of a lot better than the uppers because I was a nervous wreck. But one led to two, two led to four, four led to eight, until at the end it was about 85 a day <U+2014> the doctors could not believe I was taking that much. And that was just the [[Valium]] <U+2014> I<U+2019>m not talking about the other pills I went through".<ref name="Corey Haim interview">[http://www.thesun.co.uk/article/0,,4-2004401122,00.html Corey Haim interview] ''[[The Sun (newspaper)|The Sun]]''. Retrieved July 30, 2007.</ref>

The next year, Haim appeared in ''[[The Back Lot Murders]]'' alongside [[Priscilla Barnes]]. He became the subject of an ''[[E! True Hollywood Story]]'' in 2001. He made a [[cameo role]] appearance in ''[[Dickie Roberts: Former Child Star]]'', a film about a former [[Child actor|child star]] who did not live a normal childhood; it featured a range of other former child stars, including Feldman.

In 2002, he guest starred as himself in an episode of the Canadian television series ''[[Big Wolf on Campus]]''.

By 2004, Haim appeared to have finally overcome his drug habit, after resettling in Toronto. In response to an investigation by ''[[The Sun (newspaper)|The Sun]]'' newspaper into what exactly had happened to Haim, he responded saying that: "I'm clean, sober, humble and happy."<ref name="Corey Haim interview"/> In 2006, he was ranked #8 on [[VH1]]'s Greatest Teen Stars.

==Comeback==
On December 4, 2006, Haim began taping an improv/reality show with Feldman titled ''[[The Two Coreys]]''. The show premiered on the [[A&E Network]] on July 29, 2007. Haim and Feldman signed on for a second season of the show, which aired starting June 22, 2008.<ref>[http://www.aetv.com/the-two-coreys/about/index.jsp About the Two Coreys]</ref>

Haim was nominated for a Viewer's Choice Award at the 22nd Annual Gemini Awards in Canada for his role in ''The Two Coreys.'' He was voted #8 in the category of "Favourite Canadian" on a TV Series (not eligible for a Gemini) for his role in the A&E show.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/geminiawards/vca.html 22nd Annual Gemini Awards<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

On February 7, 2008, Haim ran a paid ad in a Hollywood trade publication, [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]], stating "This is not a stunt. I'm back. I'm ready to work. I'm ready to make amends."<ref>[http://www.coreyhaim.tv/Haim-splash.jpg/Haim-splash-full;init:.jpg Ad image]. CoreyHaim.tv.</ref>

In February 2008, filming resumed in Vancouver for ''[[Lost Boys: The Tribe]]''. Haim reversed his previous decision to not participate in the film, but did not appear on-screen until the closing credits.

Feldman stated his refusal to have further contacts with Haim until he recovered from his addiction.<ref>[http://coreyfeldman.wordpress.com/2008/08/14/the-two-coreys-the-final-episode/ The Two Coreys Final Episode]</ref> A&E decided against a third season of ''The Two Coreys'' and canceled it in July 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popcrunch.com/ae-the-two-coreys-cancelled/AE-The-Two-Coreys-Cancelled |title=The Two Coreys Cancelled}}</ref> Amid their estrangement, there were unconfirmed reports that Warner Brothers plans to release a ''Lost Boys 3'' <U+2014> with both of their characters facing off. In that scenario, [[Jamison Newlander]] would join the cast.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movieblog.ugo.com/index.php/movieblog/more/lost_boys_3_with_more_coreys_action/ |title=Lost Boys 3 with More Coreys Action}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.moviehole.net/200814558-early-lost-boys-3-talk |title=Early Lost Boys 3 Talk}}</ref> Feldman is confirmed to star in, and executive produce, ''[[Lost Boys: The Thirst]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://coreyfeldman.wordpress.com/2009/03/18/lost-boys-3-the-truth/ |title=Lost Boys 3: The Truth}}</ref>

In 2008, Haim joined the cast of ''[[Shark City]]'', which filmed in Toronto with [[Vivica Fox]], [[Carlo Rota]], [[David Phillips (actor, host)|David Phillips]], and Jefferson Brown, and premiered in 2009.  Haim was reported to be in two films scheduled for a 2010 release: ''[[The Pick Up]]'' and ''[[SAD (Standard American Diet)]]''.

==Death==
On March 10, 2010 [[KABC-TV]], [[KTLA-TV]] and [[TMZ]] reported that Corey Haim was taken to [[Providence Saint Joseph Medical Center]] in [[Burbank, California]] and pronounced dead at 2:15 a.m. (PST). According to CBS News, Haim appears to have died of an "accidental drug overdose".<ref>[http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2010/03/10/entertainment/main6284974.shtml Actor Corey Haim dies at age 38]</ref>

